    title: "Common Pitfalls in Geospatial Data Engineering",
    content: "The most common pitfall in geospatial data engineering is SRID confusion. Mixing coordinate systems without proper transformation produces spatial queries that return incorrect results or no results at all. For example, comparing a geometry in SRID 4326 (degrees) with one in SRID 3857 (meters) without transformation will silently return wrong answers because the coordinate values have completely different meanings.\n\nThe geography versus geometry type distinction in PostGIS catches many beginners. The geometry type treats coordinates as flat Cartesian values, so distance calculations do not account for Earth's curvature. The geography type treats coordinates as spherical and computes geodesic distances, but supports fewer functions. For drone data spanning small areas (under 100 km), the difference is negligible. For continental-scale analysis, it matters significantly.\n\nSpatial index maintenance is often overlooked. When large numbers of rows are inserted or updated in a table with a spatial index, the index can become fragmented and less efficient. Running REINDEX periodically maintains query performance, especially for tables with frequent writes like real-time telemetry streams.\n\nCOG creation can go wrong in subtle ways. If the source GeoTIFF has an incorrect or missing coordinate reference system, the resulting COG will produce spatially misaligned results when combined with other datasets. Always verify the source CRS before creating a COG and correct it if necessary.\n\nSTAC catalog design requires careful consideration of collection granularity. Collections that are too broad (all drone images in one collection) make searches slow and return too many results. Collections that are too narrow (one collection per flight) create catalog proliferation. The optimal granularity typically groups by sensor type, temporal campaign, and geographic region.\n\nMemory management when processing large raster files is a common operational issue. Loading a full 500-megabyte GeoTIFF into memory at once may crash the processing pipeline on memory-constrained drone edge devices. Windowed reading from COGs and block-by-block processing patterns prevent out-of-memory failures.",
